claire taylor wealth and poverty in fourth century athens stanford department of classics skip to navigation department of classics standford university logo header home people programs courses projects news events resources contact claire taylor wealth and poverty in fourth century athens mon 4 25 2011 5 15 6 45 pm building 110 room 112 450 serra mall main quad stanford ca map this talk explores ways in which to investigate the distribution of wealth and standards of living in classical athens by considering the ancient evidence in the light of the work of amartya sen we are potentially able to examine in much greater detail the lives of people outside of the wealthy elite claire taylor is a fellow at the center for hellenic studies in washington dc she has published on various aspects of greek political and social history as well as ancient graffiti she has recently edited a volume with ja baird which examines graffiti in the ancient world ancient graffiti in context and is involved in a project with k vlassopoulos which investigates subaltern groups within greek communities at the center for hellenic studies she is working on a book about wealth and poverty in fourth century attica login to post comments email stanford classics find us on facebook address & phone search upcoming events lauren ginsberg reading the aeneid in octavia's rome 02 02 2012 luca grillo power rhetoric and irony or the end of the roman republic 02 06 2012 see more recent news faculty grad student group awarded funding for shc research worshop 05 20 2011 stanford classics tops national research council rankings 09 28 2010 scit's production of aristophanes wasps in the spotlight 02 14 2011 see more news site info 2012 stanford university department of classics all rights reserved site design by chapter three login login with sunet speaker request webform for faculty stanford classics wikisite powered by drupal an open source content management system
